K mean example

tmp <- c(rnorm(30,-3), rnorm(30,3))
x <- cbind(x=tmp, y=rev(tmp))
plot(x)

Use kmeans function

k = kmeans(x, centers=2, nstart = 20)

print it out

print(k)

check ur cluster

table(k$cluster)

plot with k cluster, add cluster centers as blue points

plot(x, col = k$cluster)
# points function add features to existing plot
points(k$centers, col="blue", pch=15)

Hierarchical clustering in R

hc = hclust(dist(x))
hc
## 
## Call:
## hclust(d = dist(x))
## 
## Cluster method   : complete 
## Distance         : euclidean 
## Number of objects: 60

plot hc

plot(hc)

# draw a line to cut tree! and here u get two big branch, 2 clusters!
# height is like the distance difference
abline(h=6, col="red")
abline(h=3, col= "blue")

# return a vector of groups
grp1 = cutree(hc, h=6)
grp2 = cutree(hc, h=4)
grp3 = cutree(hc, h=3)

# define how many k group
grp4 = cutree(hc, k=2)

check ut group with table()

table(grp4)
## grp4
##  1  2 
## 31 29

plot

plot(x, col=grp4)

Slide sample

# Step 1. Generate some example data for clustering
x <- rbind(
 matrix(rnorm(100, mean=0, sd = 0.3), ncol = 2), # c1
 matrix(rnorm(100, mean = 1, sd = 0.3), ncol = 2), # c2
 matrix(c(rnorm(50, mean = 1, sd = 0.3), # c3
 rnorm(50, mean = 0, sd = 0.3)), ncol = 2))
colnames(x) <- c("x", "y")
# Step 2. Plot the data without clustering
plot(x)

# Step 3. Generate colors for known clusters
# (just so we can compare to hclust results)
col <- as.factor( rep(c("c1","c2","c3"), each=50) )
plot(x, col=col)

Make it into hc

hc = hclust(dist(x))
plot(hc)

grp5 = cutree(hc, k=3)
table(grp5, col)
##     col
## grp5 c1 c2 c3
##    1 50  0  8
##    2  0 50  7
##    3  0  0 35
plot(x, col=grp5)

prcomp function

pca = prcomp(t(mydata), scale = TRUE)
# check whats in pca
attributes(pca)
## $names
## [1] "sdev"     "rotation" "center"   "scale"    "x"       
## 
## $class
## [1] "prcomp"
# get pca components in x , and column means pca1, pca2 ....
plot(pca$x[,1], pca$x[,2])

summary(pca)

x <- read.csv("UK_foods.csv", row.names = 1)

```

pairs(x, col=rainbow(10), pch=16)

pca

pca = prcomp(t(x))
summary(pca)
## Importance of components:
##                             PC1      PC2      PC3       PC4
## Standard deviation     324.1502 212.7478 73.87622 4.189e-14
## Proportion of Variance   0.6744   0.2905  0.03503 0.000e+00
## Cumulative Proportion    0.6744   0.9650  1.00000 1.000e+00
plot(pca$x[,1], pca$x[,2], xlab="PC1", ylab="PC2", xlim=c(-270,500))
text(pca$x[,1], pca$x[,2], colnames(x), col=c("red", "blue", "green","orange"))

par(mar=c(10, 3, 0.35, 0))
barplot( pca$rotation[,1], las=2 )

## Lets focus on PC2 as it accounts for > 90% of variance 
par(mar=c(10, 3, 0.35, 0))
barplot( pca$rotation[,2], las=2 )

biplot
